04368nam a22005535i 9780889205635DE-B159720240306125748.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20061993xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97808892056357 a10.51644/97808892056352doi  a(DE-B1597)667862  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aBR1725.M3563bW37 1993eb 7aBIO0100002bisacsh04a305.42/0921 aWarne, Randi R., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLiterature as Pulpit :bThe Christian Social Activism of Nellie L. McClung /cRandi R. Warne. 1aWaterloo, Ontario : bWilfrid Laurier University Press, c[2006] 4c©1993  a1 online resource (236 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aDissertations SR00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgements -- tIntroduction -- tA Religion of Active Care: The Pearlie Watson Trilogy -- tThe Importance of Discernment: Painted Fires -- tIn Times Like These: The Anti-Feminist Context -- tIn Times Like Hers: An Analysis of In Times Like These -- tConclusion -- tAppendices -- tNellie McClung Papers,* Provincial Archives of British Columbia, Victoria, British Columbia -- tAdvertisements -- tPersonal Correspondence -- t“Letter on Militant Hysteria” by Sir Almroth Wright* -- tBibliography -- tSR Supplements0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aNellie L. McClung (1873-1951) was an internationally celebrated feminist and social activist whose success as a platform speaker was legendary. Her earliest notoriety was achieved as a writer, and during her lengthy career she authored four novels, two novellas, three collections of short stories, a two-volume autobiography and various collections of speeches, articles and wartime writing, to a total of sixteen volumes. All this served as a “pulpit” from which McClung could preach her gospel of feminist activism and social transformation. She was convinced that God’s intention for Creation was a “Fair Deal” for everyone; and that Canada, particularly the prairie West, was a perfect place to begin to bring that about. Woman suffrage, temperance and the ordination of women were keystones in the battle — engaged, in contrast to contemporary stereotypes, with a wit and compelling humour that won over enemies as it delighted her allies. Literature as Pulpit explores Nellie McClung’s vision of a “better world,” and the impediments to it, as expressed through her novels and her feminist “tract,” In Times Like These. It addresses the profoundly anti-feminist context within which McClung was forced to make her arguments, and notes her indebtedness to other feminist writers and thinkers of her day. Throughout, McClung’s religion of “active care” emerges as a consistent and harmonizing theme which integrates her feminism and social activism into a single empowering vision for social change.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aChristian biographyxCanadaxCanada. 0aChristian biographyzCanada. 4aBiography & Autobiography. 4aReligion. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Political.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978088920563540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780889205635423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780889205635/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles